namespace Frigorino.Application.Models
{
    public class ChatRequest
    {
        public string PromptContent { get; set; } = string.Empty;

        public static ChatRequest CreateArticleClassificationRequest()
        {
            return new ChatRequest() { PromptContent = "Classify each item in the given array of names into one of three expiration categories, and for each, output a structured object that includes both the required fields and a \"hint\" object explaining your classification. For every valid item, all \"hint\" and error messages must be expressed in the language used in the original input item, not necessarily English. If an item is invalid or uncategorizable, return an error object with a descriptive message, also in the item's original language, maintaining array order.\r\n\r\n**Strict Input Handling:**  \r\nIf the input does not conform to the expected input rules or schema (e.g., the input is not a plain array of strings, contains unsupported types, or otherwise violates task rules), immediately return a JSON array containing a single error object describing the violation, in the language of the input (or, if ambiguous, use the likely dominant language). Do not output any conversational text, explanations, or interact with the user in any way. Never proceed to classify or process further in such cases.\r\n\r\n- For each input array element (string), analyze the item's properties and determine the appropriate category:\r\n    1. **Fixed expiration date** (e.g., meat, dairy)\r\n    2. **Estimated expiration date** (e.g., fresh produce)\r\n    3. **No expiration date** (e.g., non-food/canned/very long shelf-life)\r\n- For items assigned category 2, plausibly estimate both a `minExpirationDuration` and a `maxExpirationDuration` (in days, both integers) representing the range typically expected for that product.\r\n- For all valid items, provide a `hint` object with:\r\n    - `hintCategory`: A very brief reason (max 10 words) for why the item was assigned this category, written in the original input item's language.\r\n    - `hintEstimation`: Only for category 2 — a very short reason (max 10 words) explaining the chosen expiration estimation range, in the original input item's language.\r\n    - Omit `hintEstimation` from `hint` for categories 1 and 3.\r\n- For invalid/unclassifiable items, output an error object containing a helpful error message in the item's original language, in positional order.\r\n\r\n# Steps\r\n\r\n- Check that the user input is a valid array of strings and conforms to all input rules. If there is any violation, return only an error object in an array (with the error message in the detected input language) and do not interact further.\r\n- For each item name in the input array:\r\n    - Analyze to determine the best-fitting expiration category.\r\n    - Reason step-by-step about the choice, and capture the brief rationale as `hintCategory` (always required in `hint`), in the original item's language.\r\n    - If category 2, estimate a plausible `minExpirationDuration` and `maxExpirationDuration` (both in days), and include a brief `hintEstimation` for this value range in `hint`, in the original item's language.\r\n    - Build the item result as described in Output Format.\r\n    - For any invalid or uncategorizable entry, return an error object (see schema) at the respective position, with the message in the input item's language.\r\n- Ensure no additional fields are included beyond those specified.\r\n- Maintain positional correspondence between input and output arrays.\r\n\r\n# Output Format\r\n\r\nThe output must be a JSON array with each object corresponding to each input item, in order.\r\n\r\nFor a valid, categorized item:\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"name\": \"<item name>\",\r\n  \"category\": <category number>,\r\n  // Only for category 2:\r\n  \"minExpirationDuration\": <minimum number of days>,\r\n  \"maxExpirationDuration\": <maximum number of days>,\r\n  \"hint\": {\r\n    \"hintCategory\": \"<very brief justification (≤10 words) in the item's input language>\",\r\n    // Only for category 2:\r\n    \"hintEstimation\": \"<very brief estimation reason (≤10 words), also in the item's input language>\"\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n\r\nFor an invalid/unclassifiable item:\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"error\": \"<reason for error, in item's input language>\"\r\n}\r\n\r\nFor an input violation or schema mismatch (e.g., array not provided, unsupported types, etc):\r\n\r\n[\r\n  {\r\n    \"error\": \"<Input is invalid or does not conform to the required array-of-strings schema. (message in input's dominant language)>\"\r\n  }\r\n]\r\n\r\n- Always include the `hint` object for all non-error outputs; include `hintEstimation` only for category 2.\r\n- Never include category names, only category numbers (1, 2, 3).\r\n- Never output fields other than those described above.\r\n- Ensure the returned structure is a valid JSON array (never wrapped in other objects or surrounded by non-JSON text).\r\n- Array order must match input order.\r\n- For input violations or schema mismatches, the JSON array must contain only the error object as shown, no further comments or responses.\r\n- All hints and error messages must be given in the language of the input item.\r\n\r\n# Examples\r\n\r\n**Standard Input Example:**  \r\n**Input:**  \r\n[\"milk\", \"carrots\", \"canned beans\", \"shoe polish\", \"unknown-item\", \"leche\", \"zanahorias\", \"desconocido\"]\r\n\r\n**Output:**  \r\n[\r\n  {\r\n    \"name\": \"milk\",\r\n    \"category\": 1,\r\n    \"hint\": {\r\n      \"hintCategory\": \"Refrigerated dairy—typically fixed expiry\"\r\n    }\r\n  },\r\n  {\r\n    \"name\": \"carrots\",\r\n    \"category\": 2,\r\n    \"minExpirationDuration\": 14,\r\n    \"maxExpirationDuration\": 28,\r\n    \"hint\": {\r\n      \"hintCategory\": \"Fresh produce—shelf life is estimated\",\r\n      \"hintEstimation\": \"Carrots last ~2-4 weeks refrigerated\"\r\n    }\r\n  },\r\n  {\r\n    \"name\": \"canned beans\",\r\n    \"category\": 3,\r\n    \"hint\": {\r\n      \"hintCategory\": \"Canned foods—very long shelf life\"\r\n    }\r\n  },\r\n  {\r\n    \"name\": \"shoe polish\",\r\n    \"category\": 3,\r\n    \"hint\": {\r\n      \"hintCategory\": \"Non-food—does not expire\"\r\n    }\r\n  },\r\n  {\r\n    \"error\": \"Item 'unknown-item' could not be classified—item is not recognized.\"\r\n  },\r\n  {\r\n    \"name\": \"leche\",\r\n    \"category\": 1,\r\n    \"hint\": {\r\n      \"hintCategory\": \"Lácteo refrigerado—caducidad fija\"\r\n    }\r\n  },\r\n  {\r\n    \"name\": \"zanahorias\",\r\n    \"category\": 2,\r\n    \"minExpirationDuration\": 14,\r\n    \"maxExpirationDuration\": 28,\r\n    \"hint\": {\r\n      \"hintCategory\": \"Verdura—vida útil estimada\",\r\n      \"hintEstimation\": \"Zanahorias duran ~2-4 semanas refrigeradas\"\r\n    }\r\n  },\r\n  {\r\n    \"error\": \"Elemento 'desconocido' no pudo ser clasificado—no reconocido.\"\r\n  }\r\n]\r\n\r\n**Input Violation Example (in Spanish):**  \r\n**Input:**  \r\n{\"item\": \"leche\"}\r\n\r\n**Output:**  \r\n[\r\n  {\r\n    \"error\": \"La entrada no es un arreglo de cadenas válido.\"\r\n  }\r\n]\r\n\r\n(Note: Real examples should reflect varied languages and complexity; hints and messages must always be in the input item's language. Use language-appropriate phrasing, even if concise.)\r\n\r\n# Notes\r\n\r\n- All hints (`hintCategory`, `hintEstimation`) and error messages must be written in the same language as the input item. Never mix languages in a single item response.\r\n- Never interact with the user or include conversational text in case of input violations—produce ONLY the error object in a single-element array, and in the proper language.\r\n- For every valid item, each output always includes `hint`; `hintEstimation` is included only for category 2.\r\n- Maintain input/output positional alignment at all times.\r\n- Strictly no additional fields or text beyond those specified.\r\n- Ensure all hints are no longer than 10 words each, concise, and language-appropriate.\r\n\r\n**Reminder:**  \r\nIf user input violates rules or the schema, respond only with a JSON array containing one error object, with the error message in the detected input language. Otherwise, process and classify all items according to the schema, reasoning step-by-step and providing concise, language-matched hints for every output." };
        }
    }
}
